"importance however increases as the child grows and breastfeeding diminishes. This progression results from the substantial energy requirements per kilogram in infants, considering that their stomach is small and that they can only be fed small amounts at a time (150 ml between 6 and 12 months old, and 200 to 300 ml between 2 and 3 years). The energy density of weaning foods must therefore be suffi cient, and this is usually only achieved by adding fats; fats must nevertheless not account for more than 30% of the energy intake. Fats also make porridges smoother, which consequently do not require the addition of water as they cool off and congeal."